In [5]:
# plot the best fit line

def line(x,y):
    
    """Fit a line in a scatter based on slope and intercept"""
    
    slope, intercept = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    line_values = [slope * i + intercept for i in x]
    plt.plot(x, line_values, 'b')
    
plt.scatter(schools.str,schools.testscr, color='lightsalmon')

plt.title('Test Scores by Student Teacher Ratio')
plt.xlabel('Student Teacher Ratio')
plt.ylabel('Average Test Scores')
line(schools.str,schools.testscr)

plt.savefig('scat4.png')
plt.show()

In [9]:
# use the style parameter

def amount_of_teachers(x):
    if x < 30:
        return 'Small'
    elif 30 <= x < 60:
        return "Medium"
    else:
        return "Large"

ax = plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))
schools['amountofteachers'] = schools['teachers'].apply(amount_of_teachers)

sns.scatterplot(x='expn_stu', y='testscr', hue='smallclass',
                style = 'amountofteachers',
                data=schools)
sns.despine()
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.xlabel('Expenditure Per Student')
plt.ylabel('Average Test Score')
ax.savefig('scat8.png')
plt.show()

                style = 'amountofteachers',

In [15]:
# show r_squared in upper left corner

from statsmodels.formula.api import ols

model1 = ols('testscr ~ expn_stu', data=schools).fit(cov_type = 'HC3')

sns.regplot(x='expn_stu', y='testscr', data = schools,
           ci=False, line_kws = {'color':'plum'},
           )

plt.annotate('Rsquared: {}'.format(round(model1.rsquared_adj,3)),
            (4000, 700))

plt.xlabel('Expenditure Per Student')
plt.ylabel('Average Test Score')

sns.despine()
plt.savefig('scat14.png')
plt.show()

converter = {0:'No', 1:'Yes'}
schools.smallclass = schools.smallclass.apply(lambda x: converter[x])

           hue = 'smallclass',
           data = schools,
           ci=False,
        palette = {'Yes':'plum','No':'lightsalmon'})
